Added JavaSearchBugsTests2#testBug381567b() which would fail if Fix v01 (i.e. the check was this.pattern.findDeclarations) was applied. Both tests pass with the tweak suggested by Satyam in comment 5 i.e. !this.pattern.findReferences.
However, I'm not sure why in order to pass the test needs to assert that the result is a "POTENTIAL_MATCH" and not an "EXACT_MATCH INSIDE_JAVADOC" as in the original JavaSearchJavadocTests#testBug83285a().

(In reply to comment #15) > However, I'm not sure why in order to pass the test needs to assert that the > result is a "POTENTIAL_MATCH" Pass JCL_LIB, the java library while the project is created. ### IJavaProject p = createJavaProject("P", new String[] { "src" }, new String[] {"JCL_LIB"}, "bin"); ### As the argument Exception couldn't be resolved, the binding is null and hence potential match is being reported.
>and not an "EXACT_MATCH INSIDE_JAVADOC" as in the > original JavaSearchJavadocTests#testBug83285a(). Adding the line "this.resultCollector.showInsideDoc();" should show the javadoc flag.
One more comment on the test. Can you also change testBug381567a() to use SearchPattern.createPattern instead of ConstructorDeclarationPattern?

(In reply to comment #16) > One more comment on the test. Can you also change testBug381567a() to use > SearchPattern.createPattern instead of ConstructorDeclarationPattern?
Sure, my first idea was to replace it with: SearchPattern pattern = SearchPattern.createPattern("b381567", CONSTRUCTOR, DECLARATIONS, SearchPattern.R_PREFIX_MATCH); but the test didn't fail without the fix.
I used ConstructorDeclarationPattern in the first place because this is what Sebastian did in comment 0.

(In reply to comment #17) > SearchPattern pattern = SearchPattern.createPattern("b381567", CONSTRUCTOR, > DECLARATIONS, SearchPattern.R_PREFIX_MATCH); > but the test didn't fail without the fix.
The test doesn't fail because org.eclipse.jdt.internal.core.search.matching.ConstructorLocator.match(MessageSend, MatchingNodeSet) being fixed here is never called.

(In reply to comment #18) > (In reply to comment #17) > > SearchPattern pattern = SearchPattern.createPattern("b381567", CONSTRUCTOR, > > DECLARATIONS, SearchPattern.R_PREFIX_MATCH); > > but the test didn't fail without the fix. > > The test doesn't fail because > org.eclipse.jdt.internal.core.search.matching.ConstructorLocator.match(MessageSend, > MatchingNodeSet) being fixed here is never called. You can leave the test as you have created. However, it will be nice to understand the reasons. There are two reasons and a test case can still be constructed.
1. In the normal course, ConstructorPattern is getting created instead of ConstructorDeclarationPattern. ConstructorPattern is filtering during the index match itself and it does mean that ConstructorDeclarationPattern can be improved to be stricter. I will file a bug to track this. The test case can be modified to include a constructor declaration in A.java. This will make it past the index match stage and ConstructorLocator.match() gets called.
2. match functions get called during the parsing pass. Next comes the resolving pass, which checks if the bindings match to the pattern. Here the matches are getting filtered. With the ConstructorDeclarationPattern, the resolve stage is being marked as unnecessary and hence further checks doesn't happen. Searching for *, is good enough to make the resolve stage unnecessary.

(In reply to comment #19)
> 1. In the normal course, ConstructorPattern is getting created instead of > ConstructorDeclarationPattern. ConstructorPattern is filtering during the index > match itself and it does mean that ConstructorDeclarationPattern can be > improved to be stricter. I will file a bug to track this. ConstructorDeclarationPattern is supposed to return default constructors too and hence it should return A.java here and it is correct. Hence not filing a bug.
